{
  "text": "There was clear demarcation between response to weight-related terms used in a medical or social context. For example, although 'Obese' was viewed as socially unacceptable, there was recognition, especially among younger people, that it would be appropriate from a health professional. While previous research demonstrated that being described as 'Obese' by a health professional encouraged men to lose weight [CITATION_1] , our study demonstrates that 'Obese' can also be motivational for women. However, a number of people seemed more comfortable with 'Clinically Obese' than 'Obese', suggesting that framing excess weight as a medical problem that can be addressed can also facilitate discussion of appropriate solutions and support [CITATION_2] .",
  "correct_citation": {
